                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="13754801" author="alex.parvulescu" created="Fri, 30 Aug 2013 15:37:46 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;fixed with &lt;a href=&quot;http://svn.apache.org/r1518984&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;http://svn.apache.org/r1518984&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13756506" author="tmueller" created="Tue, 3 Sep 2013 10:57:50 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;That doesn&apos;t sound right. Just because a full-text constraint doesn&apos;t mean a property index can&apos;t be used... Let&apos;s discuss this.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13756554" author="tmueller" created="Tue, 3 Sep 2013 12:22:51 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I forgot, index aggregates can&apos;t be supported by the PropertyIndex and NodeTypeIndex. Is this the reason to disable those indexes?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What about changing the query engine instead (as opposed to the indexes), so for such queries the query engine doesn&apos;t even &lt;em&gt;ask&lt;/em&gt; indexes that don&apos;t support aggregation? That is, if aggregation is used and a full-text index is available? I would prefer that over the PropertyIndex/NodeTypeIndex checking for full-text constraints.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13756618" author="tmueller" created="Tue, 3 Sep 2013 13:44:24 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The problem is solved. When I have time I will propose a different solution (not calling PropertyIndex and NodeTypeIndex at all for such queries), but that&apos;s a different topic.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13772711" author="alex.parvulescu" created="Fri, 20 Sep 2013 07:01:27 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Bulk close for the 0.9 release&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
